The paper deals with scheduling problems, which are typically studied in the areas of game theory (cs.GT) and algorithms (cs.DS). The concept of strategic unrelated machines also suggests a game-theoretic approach. The use of randomized algorithms and approximation ratios further supports the relevance of game theory and algorithms. The mention of social welfare as an objective also points towards the area of mechanism design (cs.MA). The use of the term "declarations" suggests the involvement of information theory (cs.IT) in the problem formulation.
